John Edward: Language skills are essential for world citizens
Scotland’s independent schools continue to stand out for academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with further outstanding test results and is only supported by individual and joint successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other joint ventures.
With more than 30,000 students from all over Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to care for their students and their parents at the highest possible level.
Independent schools pursue the goal of preparing their students for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as world citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable in schools as elective subjects.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you’ll reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.”
This is an impressive reminder that we can’t just rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s test results show that languages with the highest survival rates are at the top of the rankings of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who learned foreign languages achieved the grade A during the higher exams.
According to data collected from 74 SCIS member schools, 72% of students in Mandarin achieved the grade A during the higher exams, while 72% of students who learned German, 69% of students who learned French, and 63% of students who did not learn French.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now regarded as elective subjects as STEM subjects (sciences, engineering, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills, 17 percent of the reasons employers cited for the problems in public employment were related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly imperative when it comes to preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more open positions require languages, this knowledge is essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen profession, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage through such lifelong ability in the future.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give multilingual people an edge over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct an interview, and French was spoken as the only language by a double-digit percentage (15 percent).
For this reason, it is important for today’s children that we now invest in language lessons.
Children who speak multiple languages, especially languages of developing countries, will have better chances of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught in all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other languages will be taught, which are considered the most important for the UK in terms of 2020 such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Wherever your child’s interests lie, a number of languages with correspondingly specialized teachers will always be available at independent schools.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary for their success, no matter what the future may look like.
At this time, in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still essential for the future of the country, which is why this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should actually be regarded as “international communication capability.”
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
