This year’s course for the first time explained to students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance and also improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the University’s health services, said the university has opted for the introduction of the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, students see the image of a room in a home and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books, where they receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effects of lack of sleep on athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, and cancer.
Then, using a map of the university grounds, they are encouraged to think about their daily routine with interactive symbols.
