Why Beijing could benefit from the U.S.-China trade war
The opening waves of the U.S.-China trade war were deafening, and although the battle is not over yet, Beijing could benefit from a long-term trench between the countries, my experts say.
Donald Trump, the U.S. president, fired the first warning shot earlier this year when he seized important Chinese export goods, including solar cells, steel and aluminum, with fines.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new tariffs on $200 billion worth of goods, effectively affecting half of all goods imported from China into the US.
Beijing struck back in the same way each time and recently raised fines of five to ten percent on U.S. goods worth $60 billion.
China has vowed to respond to any U.S. action and it is unlikely that the world’s second-largest economic power will soon collapse.
Moving Washington to join would mean giving in, but a public snippet against the US would be far too tasty for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
Nevertheless, my experts believe that if Beijing plays its cards well, China could benefit from the effects of the trade war in the long term by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision could create the conditions for economic turbulence in both countries in Washington or Beijing is actually much more dangerous than many observers have previously recognized,” says Abigail Grace, a research associate at the think tank Center for New American Security.
Syria 'ready' for return of refugees, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is asking for help in rebuilding the country devastated by the more than seven-year war.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem declared that the situation in the country is improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government is rebuilding the areas destroyed by terrorists in order to restore normality.
All the conditions were now given for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their everyday lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian government welcomes aid in rebuilding the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept conditional aid from countries that had supported the uprising.
Europe wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europe won the 2018 Ryder Cup and defeated Team USA with a finish of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National near Paris.
The United States has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe won the crown back after Danish captain Thomas Bjorn’s team reached the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who had problems over a large part of the tournament, lowered his stop on the 16th track (Par 3) in the water and lost against Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all his rounds and became one of 4 players to score a 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was beaten 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in Team Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
The player with the world’s best ranking, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 to 1 against Englishman Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
Sergio Garcia, a veteran of eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“Normally I don’t cry, but today I couldn’t hold back.
It was a difficult year.
