Update on red tide: concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota are declining
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier districts, more luxuriant flowering conditions are recorded, indicating decreasing concentrations.
A red algae bloom extends over about 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but compared to last week in fewer places.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
In the last week, moderate concentrations were reported in or off the coast of the Pinellas district, low to high concentrations off the coast of the Manatee district, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the Charlotte district, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the district of Lei and Collize
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In northwestern Florida, no new respiratory problems have been reported over the past week.
